'''Katherine Elizabeth Krohn''' (born 1961) is an American author born in [[Bitburg, Germany]] to American-born parents.<ref name=Gale>{{citation |work=Biography Resource Center |title= Contemporary Authors Online |publisher= [[Gale (publisher)|Gale]] |year=2003}}</ref> Krohn is a prolific writer of books for children and young adults. Writing for young reader's series such as [[USA Today]] Lifeline Biographies and [[A&E Network|A&E]] Biography (published by Lerner Publishing Group), her works include many well-reviewed titles, such as the [[Carter G. Woodson]] Honor Book ''Ella Fitzgerald: First Lady of Song'',<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.socialstudies.org/awards/carterG/winners |publisher= National Council for the Social Studies |title= Carter G. Woodson Book Award and Honor Winners}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |work=[[Music Teachers National Association#American Music Teacher|American Music Teacher]] |date= October 2001 |page= 70}}</ref> and the [[Oregon Book Award]] contender ''Women of the Wild West''.<ref>{{citation |title= Kliatt |author= Ginsberg, Sherri Forgash |publisher= Duke School for Children |location= Chapel Hill, North Carolina |date= July 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title= Women Of The Wild West. (Good Stuff) |work=Child Life |date= January<U+2013>February 2002 |volume=27}}</ref> In recent years, Krohn ventured from the biographical format to create graphic science and graphic history titles for Capstone Press and Gale Cengage Learning. She has authored metaphysical titles about fortune-telling and ghosts, fiction, and books about contemporary social issues.

Krohn's books have received several honors, including the Carter G. Woodson Book Award, Pennsylvania School Librarians Association Young Adult Top Forty, CBC Children's Choices, and Booklist Top 10 Series Nonfiction.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Lerner Publishing Group |url=http://www.lernerbooks.com/contacts/334/Katherine-Krohn| title= About Our Author}}</ref>

Krohn lives in [[Eugene, Oregon]].<ref name=Gale/>

